summary: Supported measures to protect legitimate businesses from unfair competition by illegal and unregulated e-cigarette products, noting that illicit imports disadvantage companies that follow the law. Cosponsored the Tobacco TRACE Act to protect compliant manufacturers and distributors by establishing a national track-and-trace system with unique, tamper-resistant tracking codes to hold bad actors accountable and prevent illicit tobacco products from undercutting legitimate businesses.

Gill has criticized certain government subsidies to private firms, arguing that OCED grants (citing a $179.9 million grant to Kraft Heinz) crowd out private investment and create 'subsidy schemes.' He frames eliminating such subsidies as part of reining in wasteful government spending.

Has cosponsored bills targeting corporate subsidies and price abuses, including the End Polluter Welfare Act, Polluters Pay Climate Fund Act, and Stop Price Gouging in Grocery Stores Act, indicating support for holding corporations accountable for environmental harms and consumer price gouging.

Has publicly celebrated major employers and corporations as drivers of local and state economic growth. Introduced a bipartisan resolution commemorating Delta Air Lines' 100-year anniversary, noting Delta's impact as a major employer in his district, its corporate presence in Georgia, and its role in business growth, infrastructure investments, and community partnerships. Also led bipartisan congressional action to protect Rinnai America Corporation's Griffin manufacturing facility by repealing a federal regulation that threatened its production of non-condensing tankless water heaters, an effort explicitly framed as saving local manufacturing jobs and preserving American-made production. Rinnai's leadership publicly thanked him for his engagement in bringing the rule to the Department of Energy's attention and credited him with preserving the plant and its workers. Continued to partner with and spotlight local manufacturersmost recently ALTA Refrigeration (150 employees)helping navigate and seek relief from federal regulations (including EPA rules) he describes as job-killing, and hosted Vice President Vance and Cabinet officials at a local manufacturing event to promote deregulation and federal support for American businesses. Recently convened a bipartisan hearing on the economic impact of Minor League Baseball, featuring executives from Diamond Baseball Holdings and team owners, highlighting the role that team ownership and sports-related enterprises play in driving local economic activity and supporting small business partners. Also secured endorsements from five major arena operators (AEG, Legends Global, Madison Square Garden Entertainment, MGM Resorts International, and Oak View Group) for the Muhammad Ali American Boxing Revival Act (H.R.4624), highlighting partnerships with large venue operators and the bill's role in bringing marquee boxing events and related economic activity back to U.S. arenas such as State Farm Arena, Madison Square Garden, Crypto.com Arena, and others.
